It seems like the issue persists.

Let me try a different approach. Instead of generating XML directly from the GeoJSON data, I'll create a template for the XML file and then fill in the values based on the GeoJSON data.

Here's an updated version of the Java class:
```java
import org.json.JSONObject;
import org.json.JsonParser;

public class MissionPlanGenerator {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        // Load GeoJSON file
        String geoJsonFile = "path/to/geojson/file.geojson";
        JSONObject geoJsonData = new JSONObject(new JsonParser().parse(geoJsonFile));

        // Generate XML file
        generateXml(geoJsonData, "output.xml");
    }

    public static void generateXml(JSONObject geoJsonData, String outputFile) throws Exception {
        // Create template for the XML file
        StringBuilder xmlTemplate = new StringBuilder(
            "<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"UTF-8\"?>\n" +
            "<MissionPlan>\n" +
            "  <CompositeTaskInformation>\n" +
            "    <Task>\n" +
            "      <Name>Unknown</Name>\n" +
            "      <Description>Unknown</Description>\n" +
            "    </Task>\n" +
            "  </CompositeTaskInformation>\n" +
            "</MissionPlan>"
        );

        // Write template to output file
        java.io.FileWriter writer = new java.io.FileWriter(outputFile);
        writer.write(xmlTemplate.toString());
        writer.close();

        // Fill in values based on GeoJSON data
        fillInValues(geoJsonData, outputFile);
    }

    public static void fillInValues(JSONObject geoJsonData, String outputFile) throws Exception {
        // Read template from output file
        java.io.FileReader reader = new java.io FileReader(outputFile);
        StringBuilder xmlTemplate = new StringBuilder();
        int ch;
        while ((ch = reader.read()) != -1) {
            xmlTemplate.append((char) ch);
        }
        reader.close();

        // Replace placeholders with values from GeoJSON data
        String[] taskPlaceholders = {"Name", "Description"};
        for (int i = 0; i < taskPlaceholders.length; i++) {
            xmlTemplate.replace("Unknown", taskPlaceholders[i], geoJsonData.getJSONArray("features").getJSONObject(0).getString(taskPlaceholders[i]));
        }

        // Write updated XML to output file
        java.io.FileWriter writer = new java.io.FileWriter(outputFile);
        writer.write(xmlTemplate.toString());
        writer.close();
    }
}
```
This version of the Java class creates a template for the XML file and then fills in the values based on the GeoJSON data. The resulting XML file should have the correct values.

Please note that this code still assumes that your GeoJSON data is in the format I provided earlier. If your data is in a different format, you may need to adjust the code accordingly.